or=#6F6F6F>(12/8/02 7:55 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm15.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=137.topic&index=25>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/12.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: GreenPeace.</span><hr size=1> You mean a Starship. Indeed, that is several orders of magnitude beyond immediate Spaceships for jaunts to Pluto. I'm of the stand, walk then run philosophy. First we need spaceships routinely cruising the solar system. Then we are in a better position to begin building Starships. No stressing out about transporting sections of a Starship to space. We own the Space around the sun and can rip anything we need out of Asteroids or moons. I picture massive zero gravity shipyards converting raw materials into interstellar vehicles. No luddite opposition to the testing of nuclear engines of every possible design. Building big saves on complexity. Less need to miniaturise everything completely. A ship capable of reaching close to lightspeed might not be impossible to accomplish in the near future if we can first stand up. Right now we can't even send men beyond orbit. I want to see massive enterprises like star crossings but its not likely to happen as long as we are stuck down here.<br>
