 align=absmiddle>  Re: GreenPeace.</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The beams would shoot out at the speed of light because your stationary in relation to them. It would be like being in a ship going the speed of light and then turning on a flashlight.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I'm not sure I buy that... speed is relative of course.  If I'm riding in the back of a bus that is traveling at 100 kph and I toss a baseball towards the front at 50 kph then to me and all of the passengers it 'appears' to travel at 50 kph, but to an observer standing on the side of the road, the baseball would be traveling at 150 kph which is it's actual velocity to the rest of the universe.  So the baseball will interact with the rest of the universe as if it's traveling at the combined speed of the pitch (50 kph) and the bus velocity (100 kph) for a total of 150 kph.  In other words, if I tossed the ball forward and out of the window at the poor guy standing along side the road, the impact on his head would be 150 kph.<br>
<br>
The hypothetical light speed traveling car's headlights, when switched on, would be interacting with the rest of the universe, not just inside (relative to) the car and it's occupants.  So the headlights, shackled by Einstein, wouldn't work. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mauk2>Mauk2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 164<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/13/02 10:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm15.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=137.topic&index=35>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: GreenPeace.</span><hr size=1> Another way of thinking about relativistic effects is to consider that space has 4 dimensions, not three.  Time is, of course, the 4th dimension.  <br>
<br>
The important part to remember is that EVERYTHING in the Universe is ALWAYS moving at exactly the same speed, its just that some things are moving in different dimensions than others.<br>
<br>
So, if you are sitting in your Edsel in the driveway, you are not moving at all in space, but you are fairly TEARING along through time.  You just don't notice it because everything else is racing through time at the same speed.<br>
<br>
<br>
So, you fill up your tank with antimatter, and soon you are in your Edsel clipping along at 99.999 percent of lightspeed.  However, you will remember above that everything in the Universe always has to move at the same speed.  What happens is you have moved most of your speed from time motion to space motion, therefore you seem frozen into immobility from a time perspective.<br>
<br>
The beauty of Relativity is that the amount of increase or decrease in your time and space speeds are relative to each other.  Sitting in you ultra-fast Edsel, the light from your headlights seems to zip away just like normal, because you have slowed down in time exactly as much as you have sped up in space.<br>
<br>
See how that works?  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
